    <p>Magnesium is the fourth most abundant mineral in the human body and a cofactor in over 300 enzymatic reactions — yet an estimated 48% of Americans consume less than the recommended daily amount. The consequences extend far beyond muscle cramps. Magnesium plays a direct role in sleep regulation through its effects on GABA receptors, melatonin synthesis, and the hypothalamic-pituitary-adrenal (HPA) axis. When magnesium levels drop below optimal, the nervous system stays in a state of heightened excitability that makes falling asleep — and staying asleep — significantly harder.</p>

    <p>This guide covers everything the clinical literature tells us about magnesium and sleep: which forms work best, the correct dosage, optimal timing, side effects, and how it stacks with other popular sleep supplements like melatonin and <a href="/sleep/l-theanine-gummies/">L-theanine gummies</a>. If you are considering magnesium supplementation for sleep, this is the most comprehensive evidence-based resource available.</p>

    <div class="key-stat">
