    <p><strong>Our recommendation:</strong> For sleep, choose magnesium glycinate as your primary form. If brain fog, memory, or age-related cognitive decline is a concern alongside sleep, magnesium L-threonate (branded as Magtein) is the superior choice because it is the only form clinically demonstrated to cross the blood-brain barrier and elevate brain magnesium concentrations. Avoid magnesium oxide entirely — its 4-5% absorption rate means a 400mg capsule delivers roughly 16-20mg of usable magnesium while causing significant GI distress.</p>

    <!-- SECTION 4: GLYCINATE VS CITRATE -->
    <h2>Magnesium Glycinate vs Citrate for Sleep</h2>

    <p>This is the most common question in magnesium supplementation, and the answer is unambiguous: magnesium glycinate is superior to magnesium citrate for sleep. The two forms differ in three clinically relevant ways. For our detailed head-to-head breakdown with product recommendations, read our full <a href="/sleep/magnesium-glycinate-vs-citrate/">magnesium glycinate vs citrate</a> comparison.</p>

    <div class="info-cards">
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="award" size={22} /></div>
        <h3>Magnesium Glycinate</h3>
        <p><strong>Winner for sleep.</strong> Chelated with glycine — an amino acid that independently activates GABA receptors and lowers core body temperature. High bioavailability. Does not cause diarrhea or GI distress at therapeutic doses. Gentle enough for daily long-term use. This is what most sleep-focused supplements use.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="zap" size={22} /></div>
        <h3>Magnesium Citrate</h3>
        <p><strong>Better for general supplementation.</strong> Bound to citric acid. Decent bioavailability but well-known for its osmotic laxative effect — it draws water into the intestines. At sleep-relevant doses (300-400mg), many people experience loose stools. Works for magnesium repletion but the GI side effects make it suboptimal as a nightly sleep supplement.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p>The glycine component of magnesium glycinate is what gives it a decisive advantage for sleep. A 2015 study in <em>Neuropsychopharmacology</em> found that 3g of glycine before bed improved subjective sleep quality, reduced sleep onset latency, and decreased daytime sleepiness — effects that were attributed to glycine's ability to lower core body temperature and activate NMDA receptors in the suprachiasmatic nucleus (the brain's master circadian clock). When you take magnesium glycinate, you get the sleep benefits of both magnesium and glycine simultaneously.</p>

