    <!-- SECTION 9: SIGNS OF DEFICIENCY -->
    <h2>Signs You're Magnesium Deficient</h2>

    <p>Magnesium deficiency rarely produces dramatic symptoms — it manifests as a collection of vague, chronic complaints that many people attribute to stress, aging, or poor sleep habits. The irony is that these symptoms are both caused by and contribute to poor sleep, creating a vicious cycle. If you experience three or more of the following, magnesium deficiency is a strong possibility worth investigating with your physician.</p>

    <div class="info-cards">
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="moon" size={22} /></div>
        <h3>Difficulty Falling or Staying Asleep</h3>
        <p>Insomnia — particularly difficulty with sleep onset and frequent nighttime awakenings — is one of the earliest signs of subclinical magnesium deficiency. The brain cannot activate GABA receptors efficiently without adequate magnesium.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="activity" size={22} /></div>
        <h3>Muscle Cramps and Twitching</h3>
        <p>Involuntary muscle contractions, especially calf cramps at night, eyelid twitching, and restless legs are classic signs. Magnesium regulates calcium channels in muscle cells — without it, muscles contract excessively.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="alert-circle" size={22} /></div>
        <h3>Anxiety and Irritability</h3>
        <p>Low magnesium increases HPA axis activity and cortisol output, creating a state of chronic low-grade anxiety. Many people are prescribed anti-anxiety medication when magnesium supplementation would address the root cause.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="battery" size={22} /></div>
        <h3>Chronic Fatigue</h3>
        <p>Magnesium is required for ATP production — the energy currency of every cell. Deficiency impairs cellular energy production, leading to persistent tiredness that sleep alone cannot resolve.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="zap" size={22} /></div>
        <h3>Frequent Headaches</h3>
        <p>Magnesium deficiency is a recognized contributor to tension headaches and migraines. The American Academy of Neurology and American Headache Society include magnesium in their migraine prevention guidelines.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="heart" size={22} /></div>
        <h3>Heart Palpitations</h3>
        <p>Magnesium regulates heart rhythm. Deficiency can cause benign but alarming palpitations, premature ventricular contractions (PVCs), and a sensation of the heart "skipping" beats.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="tip-box">
      <span class="tip-box-ico">💡</span>
      <p><strong>Testing note:</strong> Standard serum magnesium blood tests are unreliable because only 1% of the body's magnesium is in the blood — the rest is in bones and soft tissue. A red blood cell (RBC) magnesium test is more accurate for detecting subclinical deficiency. Ask your physician specifically for an RBC magnesium test if you suspect deficiency.</p>
    </div>

