    <!-- SECTION 11: SIDE EFFECTS AND SAFETY -->
    <h2>Side Effects and Safety</h2>

    <p>Magnesium supplementation is generally safe for healthy adults at recommended doses. It has a wide therapeutic window and has been used in clinical settings for decades. That said, there are specific populations and situations where caution is warranted.</p>

    <h3>Common Side Effects</h3>

    <p>The most frequent side effect is gastrointestinal disturbance — loose stools, diarrhea, nausea, and abdominal cramping. These effects are dose-dependent and form-dependent. Magnesium citrate and magnesium oxide are the most likely to cause GI issues because they draw water into the intestines via osmosis. Magnesium glycinate, taurate, and threonate cause significantly fewer GI side effects and are preferred for daily nighttime use.</p>

    <div class="warn-box">
      <span class="warn-box-ico">⚠️</span>
      <p><strong>Kidney disease warning:</strong> People with impaired kidney function (eGFR below 60 mL/min) should NOT take magnesium supplements without physician approval. The kidneys are responsible for excreting excess magnesium. When kidney function is impaired, magnesium can accumulate to dangerous levels (hypermagnesemia), causing muscle weakness, difficulty breathing, irregular heartbeat, and in severe cases, cardiac arrest. This is a serious and potentially life-threatening condition. If you have any history of kidney disease, consult your nephrologist before taking magnesium.</p>
    </div>

