    <p>For the vast majority of healthy adults, magnesium glycinate at 200-400mg before bed is safe, well-tolerated, and carries no risk of dependency or withdrawal. Unlike prescription sleep aids, magnesium does not impair next-day cognitive function, does not cause rebound insomnia, and can be stopped at any time without tapering.</p>

    <!-- FAQ -->
    <section class="faq-sec">
      <h2>Magnesium for Sleep — Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Does magnesium help you fall asleep faster?</summary><p>Yes. Clinical studies show magnesium supplementation reduces sleep onset latency by an average of 12-17 minutes. Magnesium activates GABA receptors in the brain — the same receptors targeted by prescription sleep medications. A 2012 RCT in the <em>Journal of Research in Medical Sciences</em> found that 500mg of magnesium daily for 8 weeks significantly improved sleep onset and overall sleep quality compared to placebo.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>What is the best form of magnesium for sleep?</summary><p>Magnesium glycinate is the best overall form for sleep. The glycine amino acid has independent calming effects on the nervous system, and the compound has high bioavailability with minimal GI side effects. Magnesium L-threonate (Magtein) is the best for brain health because it crosses the blood-brain barrier. Both are well-tolerated at bedtime doses of 200-400mg elemental magnesium.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>How much magnesium should I take before bed?</summary><p>The therapeutic dose range for sleep is 200-400mg of elemental magnesium taken 1-2 hours before bed. The NIH Tolerable Upper Intake Level for supplemental magnesium is 350mg/day for adults. Start with 200mg and increase if needed. Always check the label for elemental magnesium content — not just the total weight of the magnesium compound.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Can I take magnesium with melatonin?</summary><p>Yes, safely. They work through complementary mechanisms: melatonin signals your circadian clock, while magnesium activates the parasympathetic nervous system. Use 200-400mg magnesium glycinate with 0.5-3mg melatonin, both taken 1-2 hours before bed. No known adverse interactions at standard doses.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>How long does it take for magnesium to improve sleep?</summary><p>Some people notice improved relaxation within the first week. However, clinical studies show the most significant improvements at 4-8 weeks of consistent daily use. Magnesium works by gradually correcting a deficiency and rebalancing neurotransmitter activity — it is not an acute sedative.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Is magnesium safe for kids?</summary><p>Magnesium is generally safe for children at age-appropriate doses. The NIH RDA ranges from 80mg (ages 1-3) to 240mg (ages 9-13). Supplemental magnesium for children should not exceed the Tolerable Upper Intake Level (65mg ages 1-3, 110mg ages 4-8, 350mg ages 9-18). Always consult a pediatrician before supplementing children.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Does magnesium help with anxiety and sleep?</summary><p>Yes, through overlapping mechanisms. Magnesium activates GABA-A receptors, regulates the HPA axis (lowering cortisol), and supports serotonin synthesis. A 2017 systematic review in <em>Nutrients</em> confirmed magnesium supplementation has beneficial effects on subjective anxiety. Since anxiety is a leading cause of insomnia, reducing anxiety with magnesium often improves sleep as a secondary benefit.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>What are the side effects of magnesium for sleep?</summary><p>The most common side effect is loose stools or diarrhea — most likely with magnesium citrate and oxide. Magnesium glycinate and threonate cause fewer GI issues. People with kidney disease should avoid supplements because impaired kidneys cannot excrete excess magnesium, risking hypermagnesemia. Stay within the NIH UL of 350mg supplemental magnesium per day.</p></details>
    </section>

